## 10. AI Integration (CLAUDE.md)

If you use an AI coding assistant (Claude Code, Gemini CLI, etc.) with your vault, place a `CLAUDE.md` file at the vault root. This file is automatically loaded as context, giving the AI agent full awareness of your vault's structure, rules, and workflows.

### What to put in CLAUDE.md

```markdown
# [Your Name]'s Second Brain

## Who I am
[Brief: your role, active projects, areas you care about]

## System
Outer shell: I+PARA (Inbox → Projects → Areas → Resources → Archive)
Inner core: Zettelkasten (Literature Notes → Slip-Box of atomic permanent notes)
Note lifecycle: fleeting → literature → permanent
Maturity: seedling → budding → evergreen

## Folder map
[Copy the folder map from Section 4]

## Core rules
[Copy the rules from Section 11]

## Tag taxonomy
[Copy your tag taxonomy]

## How to respond to common prompts

"Create today's journal entry"
→ Use daily-journal template, name YYYY-MM-DD.md, save to 02-Journal/Daily/

"Process my inbox"
→ Read 01-Inbox/Now/, classify each note, rename, move, report what moved

"Create a literature note for [source]"
→ Use literature-note template, name LitNote-AuthorTitle-Year.md

"Extract permanent notes"
→ Use permanent-note template, one idea only, timestamp filename

"Start weekly review"
→ Use weekly-review template, follow CLEAR framework

"What do I have on [topic]?"
→ Search all folders, summarize findings, suggest connections
```

### Tips for AI integration
- Keep `CLAUDE.md` **terse** — it is loaded into every session. Shorter = fewer tokens consumed = more context left for actual work.
- Put full schemas and workflows in `VAULT-MANUAL.md` and have `CLAUDE.md` point there.
- Update both files whenever you change the vault structure.
- If you use multiple AI tools, create `GEMINI.md`, `CURSOR.md`, etc. with the same structure but tool-specific behaviors.

