## 11. Rules to Live By

These are the rules that make the system work. Breaking them creates debt you'll pay later.

1. **Everything enters `01-Inbox/Now/` first** — no exceptions. Even if you know exactly where something goes, capture first, sort later. This protects your flow state.

2. **Permanent notes: one idea only** — if the title contains "and", split it. Atomic notes link more precisely and age better.

3. **Literature notes: your own words** — never copy-paste. The discomfort of translation is where learning happens. If you can't paraphrase it, you don't understand it yet.

4. **Never delete** — move to `06-Archive/` instead. What feels useless today may be exactly what you need in six months. Deletion has no undo.

5. **Tags from the taxonomy only** — never invent new tags in the moment. If a new tag seems necessary, stop and deliberately decide whether to add it to the taxonomy. Ad-hoc tagging creates noise.

6. **All internal links use `[[WikiLinks]]`** — not `[text](path)`. WikiLinks survive file renames. Markdown paths don't.

7. **Slip-Box is always flat** — `MOCs/` is the only subfolder allowed. Folders in the Slip-Box defeat the purpose of the system. If you feel the urge to create a subfolder, create a MOC instead.

8. **Frontmatter always uses `---` delimiters** — tags without `#` in YAML.

9. **Update your manual** — whenever you change a folder, add a template, or modify the tag taxonomy, update `VAULT-MANUAL.md`. Future-you will thank present-you.

10. **Done beats perfect** — a seedling note in the vault beats a perfect note that never got written. Capture first. Refine later.

