## 12. Tips for Long-Term Success

**Start small.** Don't try to organize everything on day one. The system is for new information coming in. Don't migrate your entire file system — that way lies a month of procrastination with nothing to show.

**The inbox is your best friend.** The biggest failure mode for PKM systems is friction at capture time. `01-Inbox/Now/` exists precisely to remove that friction. Something goes in there in 10 seconds; sorting it takes 2 minutes later when you have focus.

**Quantity over quality, early on.** Your first 100 permanent notes will be rough. Write them anyway. You can't refine notes you haven't written.

**Links are more valuable than folders.** A note connected to 5 others is worth more than 5 unconnected notes in a perfectly named folder. When you create a permanent note, always ask: what 2–3 other notes does this connect to?

**Weekly reviews are non-negotiable.** The system compounds because of weekly reviews. Skipping them for two weeks means your inbox fills up, your notes lose context, and the whole thing starts to feel like a burden. 30 minutes once a week is all it takes.

**Promote notes deliberately.** A seedling that never gets promoted is a dead end. When you revisit a note, ask: has this idea connected to others? Is it stable? Can it become budding or evergreen? The maturity system is only useful if you actually use it.

**The goal is outputs, not organization.** The system exists to make you think better, write faster, and decide more clearly — not to have a beautiful folder structure. If maintaining the structure is taking more time than using it produces, simplify.

